entries.name: VotingV2
entries.description: Core smart contract for UMA's Data Verification Mechanism (DVM), serving as source of truth for disputed claims. UMA token holders collectively resolve price requests and earn rewards for correct participation. Commit- and reveal phases for the voting take 1d each.

entries.name: OptimisticGovernor
entries.description: Optimistic Governance module allowing for proposals by anyone with a bond of 2 WETH. They become executable if not challenged within 2d. The rules for proposals can be read directly from the contract values.

receivedPermissions.description: update configuration values.
set guard, avatar, target, delay, identifier, escalationManager, bond token and amount.

pause the system, manage all fees, bonds and security parameters, manage tokens and chain support, and critical emergency actions like admin functions on remote SpokePools or deleting proposals (can steal funds).
manage the proposer role.

values.rules: I assert that this transaction proposal is valid according to the following rules: Proposals approved on Snapshot, as verified at https://snapshot.org/#/acrossprotocol.eth, are valid as long as there is a minimum quorum of 6000000 and a minimum voting period of 72 hours and it does not appear that the Snapshot voting system is being exploited or is otherwise unavailable. The quorum and voting period are minimum requirements for a proposal to be valid. Quorum and voting period values set for a specific proposal in Snapshot should be used if they are more strict than the rules parameter. The explanation included with the on-chain proposal must be the unique IPFS identifier for the specific Snapshot proposal that was approved or a unique identifier for a proposal in an alternative voting system approved by DAO social consensus if Snapshot is being exploited or is otherwise unavailable.

rules.description: string of rules that a proposer is accepting when posting a proposal with a bond.

entries.name: HubPool
entries.description: The central L1 contract (hub) that manages liquidity from LPs and coordinates cross-chain settlements. It receives and secures settlement proposals (root bundles) using the UMA Optimistic Oracle, with a challenge period of 1h and a bond amount of 0.45 ABT.

directlyReceivedPermissions.description: relay and delete root bundles, pause the contract, manage routes, set the withdrawal recipient (crosschain rebalancing target).

entries.name: IdentifierWhitelist
entries.description: Keeps a list of whitelisted identifiers that are accepted by the UMA v3 protocol. Across uses the identifier `ACROSS-V2` for its disputes.

entries.name: AddressWhitelist
entries.description: A simple address whitelist for tokens that can be used as bonds and/or fees. This whitelist is checked and enforced by various smart contracts in the UMA ecosystem.

entries.name: AcrossBondToken (ABT)
entries.description: A bond token wrapping ETH for usage in the Across protocol. Implements modified ERC20 logic to only allow permissioned proposers to use it as a bond for root bundle proposals.

entries.name: SkinnyOptimisticOracle
entries.description: Validates bridge messages by allowing proposers to make bonded assertions about crosschain events. It enforces a challenge period during which any invalid claims can be disputed and escalated to UMA's Data Verification Mechanism (DVM) for resolution.

entries.name: OptimisticOracleV3
entries.description: Standard UMA optimistic oracle contract that allows anyone to make an arbitrary claim by posting a bond. The claim is considered true unless it is successfully disputed within a challenge window, with UMA's DVM acting as the final arbiter for disputes.
